  <subsubsection|Elementary equations>

  \;

  We start from the angle <math|\<theta\>> as a given, of course it's not an
  observable angle, but it's easier to go from it.

  From isocele triangle <math|<wide|AOB|^>>, we easily get that:

  <\equation>
    <inactive|<label|eq1>>\<beta\>=<frac|\<pi\>|2>-\<theta\>
  </equation>

  \;

  Taking rectangle triange <math|<wide|AFC|^>>, we get:

  <\equation>
    <inactive|<label|eq2>>FC=h <math-up|sin><around*|(|\<beta\>|)>
  </equation>

  <\equation>
    <inactive|<label|eq3>>FA=h <math-up|cos><around*|(|\<beta\>|)>
  </equation>

  \;

  We can also note that:

  <\equation>
    <inactive|<label|eq4>>FB=AB-FA
  </equation>

  \;

  Taking rectangle triange <math|<wide|OHA|^>>, we get:

  <\equation>
    <inactive|<label|eq5>>AH=r <math-up|sin><around*|(|\<theta\>|)>
  </equation>

  \;

  Thus:

  \;

  <\equation>
    <inactive|<label|eq6>>AB=2r <math-up|sin><around*|(|\<beta\>|)>
  </equation>

  \;

  Taking rectangle triange <math|<wide|BFC|^>>, we get:

  <\equation>
    <label|eq7><math-up|tan><around*|(|\<delta\>|)>=<frac|FC|FB>
  </equation>

  \;

  Thus:

  \;

  <\equation>
    <label|eq8>\<delta\>=<math-up|atan><around*|(|<frac|FC|FB>|)>
  </equation>

  \;

  The incidence angle <math|i> is:

  \;

  <\equation>
    <label|eq9>i=\<beta\>-\<delta\>
  </equation>

  \;

  Taking triange <math|<wide|ABE|^>>, we get:

  <\equation>
    <inactive|<label|eq10>>\<alpha\>+\<delta\>+\<beta\>+<frac|\<pi\>|2>=\<pi\>
  </equation>

  \;

  Thus (using equation <reference|eq1>):

  <\equation>
    <label|eq11>\<alpha\>=\<theta\>-\<delta\>
  </equation>

  \;

